Implemented Vercel Speed Insights for the React + Vite frontend application.

## Changes Made:

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/speed-insights` package (version 1.0.15) using npm
- Updated package.json to include the new dependency
- Updated package-lock.json with the new dependency tree

### 2. Code Configuration
Modified `/frontend/src/App.jsx`:
- Added import statement: `import { SpeedInsights } from '@vercel/speed-insights/react';`
- Added `<SpeedInsights />` component alongside the existing `<Analytics />` component
- The component is placed inside the AuthProvider context to ensure it has access to authentication state if needed

### 3. Implementation Details
- Followed the official Vercel Speed Insights documentation for React applications
- The SpeedInsights component is positioned at the same level as the Analytics component
- This ensures performance metrics are tracked across all routes in the application
- No additional configuration required - the component works out of the box

### 4. Verification
- Build completed successfully with `npm run build`
- No errors or warnings during the build process
- The Speed Insights script will be automatically injected when deployed to Vercel

## How It Works:
The SpeedInsights component automatically:
1. Tracks Core Web Vitals (LCP, FID, CLS, FCP, TTFB, INP)
2. Reports performance metrics to Vercel's analytics dashboard
3. Provides real user monitoring data for performance optimization

## Next Steps:
- Deploy to Vercel to activate Speed Insights data collection
- View performance metrics in the Vercel dashboard under the Speed Insights tab
- Monitor and optimize based on real user performance data

Files modified:
- frontend/package.json
- frontend/package-lock.json
- frontend/src/App.jsx
